      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A p-value of 0.06, while hovering near the .05 threshold, is still technically not statistically significant, meaning the data doesn't provide strong enough evidence to rule out chance. You can't just declare it significant because the trend is \"pretty clear\" in the graph; the p-value is the formal statistical measure of that evidence. To explain this without sounding like a failure, you can frame it as a \"trend towards significance\" or a \"marginal finding.\" This acknowledges the pattern while honestly reporting the statistical outcome.",
      "source": "target",
